Although this particular article does not give a *percentage *of vets who are homeless. The figure of 250,000 is a very large number of homeless vets.<br><br>
Perhaps next time you see a homeless person, you may see a man with a history - who has served his country - instead of a BUM.<br><br>
The following is from the Air force News Service of 21Mar97:<br>
************************************************************<br>
VA marks 10 years of service to homeless veterans<br><br>
WASHINGTON (AFNS) -- The Department of Veterans Affairs is marking the 10th<br>
anniversary of legislation authorizing it to establish specialized programs<br>
for homeless veterans, including treatment and rehabilitation of those<br>
suffering from mental and addictive disorders.<br><br>
&quot;This country's 250,000 homeless veterans, many of whom served in a war<br>
zone, now face the daily battles of life on the streets, battles that are<br>
fought in poverty and isolation, pain and confusion.  In the last 10 years,<br>
VA has offered help, opportunity and hope to homeless veterans struggling<br>
for their dignity and very survival, &quot; said VA Secretary Jesse Brown.<br><br>

